parent robustness of\nmachine learning techniques, whether on space-based or the qualitatively\ndifferent ground-based data, highlights their importance to future surveys such\nas TESS and PLATO and the need to better understand their advantages and\npitfalls in an exoplanetary context.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 May 2018 08:23:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-06-06"}
{"id":"1805.07090","submitter":"Michael Zaiser","authors":"David Fernandez Castellanos, Michael Zaiser","title":"Avalanche behavior in creep failure of disordered materials","comments":"5 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 121, 125501 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.121.125501","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.dis-nn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a mesoscale elastoplastic model of creep in disordered materials\nwhich considers temperature-dependent stochastic activation of localized\ndeformation events which are mutually coupled by internal stresses, leading to\ncollective avalanche dynamics. We generalize this stochastic plasticity model\nby introducing damage in terms of a local strength that decreases, on\nstatistical average, with increasing local plastic strain. As a consequence the\nmodel captures failure in terms of strain localization in a catastrophic shear\nband concomitant with a finite-time singularity of the creep rate. The\nstatistics of avalanches in the run-up to failure is characterized by a\ndecreasing avalanche exponent $\\tau$ that, at failure, approaches the value\n$\\tau = 1.5$ typical of a critical branching process. The average avalanche\nrate exhibits an inverse Omori law as a function of the time-to-failure,\nwhereas the distribution of inter-avalanche times turns out to be consistent\nwith the ETAS model of earthquake statistics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 May 2018 08:27:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-09-26"}
